The White House has said the nuclear deal is not happening 'anytime soon.' In fact, according to CNN, a UN envoy for Iran has stated that the nuclear deal is 'not even on the agenda.' Further, Iran's providing Russia with armed drones as reported by The Guardian may complicate things further. Then we have the technicality of having the deal be effective. If a deal is reached, it takes time to draft the official agreement. Then the agreement has to take effect on a certain date, and at this point the most logical time is the first day of 2023, which would resolve this question NO. I leave an extra percentage point or two to acknowledge the fact that it takes the average deal approximately 26 months to complete, which this renegotiation is soon approaching. There are also possibilities that conditions materialize that the deal could be used as leverage for something else.

A major, controversial foreign policy decision this close to midterms is unlikely, especially given the criticism of Biden's other foreign policy moves and the focus on Ukraine. Additionally, there are still major roadblocks in talks between US and Iran, and far more pressing domestic concerns for Biden. Republicans are already campaigning on Democrat failures in Afghanistan, and rejoining the JCPOA wouldn't help. It is possible though, and American foreign policy concerns and news focus could shift in the next several months.
The USA is distracted with the Russia-Ukraine issue and will be less likely to move on such a politically hot topic like the Iran nuke deal.

Iran has dropped significantly as a foreign policy priority (i.e. Russian possible invasion of Ukraine and China messing with Taiwan, again). Also, Iran really has no interest in the U.S. rejoining the agreement.
With the iranian side willing to let go of some high demands, there is a high chance of the US joining JCPOA this year.

Rejoining the JCOPA is a Biden priority, and they have the personnel to resurrect the deal. However, I don’t think the Administration would announce/sign something this controversial before the mid-term elections. Further, if Russia invades Ukraine, which is likely, the EU and the US would not want Russia to be part of the negotiations, which would be problem for Iran. On the other hand, reduced Russian oil and gas exports would increase pressure to bring Iran production back to the world market.

Unlikely. There is no political will at the moment to accomplish anything. The only political will available at the moment is to stop the other side from making a policy decision. Obstructionism will keep the US from rejoining the JCPOA unless it can be done solely by Presidential Order (but I don't believe it can be)
US leadership will be looking for "winning" opportunities outside of domestic covid progress. This is one opportunity where ground could be made.

The US and Iran would need to simultaneously rejoin the JCPOA in order for either to rejoin, necessarily reducing the chances of the US rejoining. Iran wants reassurances that the US will not withdraw again and knows that Republicans are likely to retake the House and Senate in the November midterm elections, making anti-JCPOA legislation (and/or withdrawal by a future Administration) a distinct possibility. The Biden Administration would thus need to make significant concessions to the Iranians to get them to rejoin. Biden's willingness for this is likely to increase as his domestic agenda is frustrated, and Iran might likewise become more willing as its economy continues to flag and a deal with Biden could garner some short-term relief, but there's no clear triggering incentive to tip either country over into rejoining until closer to the end of Biden's term.

US waffling due to changes of administration (Trump, Biden) is likely impacting Iran's confidence in the US will to follow through with whatever is agreed. They are not taking the US seriously IAW this article. https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2021-12-04/u-s-says-chances-of-rejoining-iran-nuclear-deal-may-slip-away

The Biden Administration really needs a major foreign policy victory. This will be a prime target for them in 2023, but Iran does not appear to be serious about the negotiations. So, the question on this is, what is the United States willing to give that Iran really wants in order for the rejoining to occur?

Apparently the diplomats are saying there's progress happening, but we heard that for the entire second half of 2021, which I made the mistake of putting some trust in. So I'll go with just below a 1 in 3 chance for now, and I'm going to drop more aggressively this time around if we don't concrete signs of progress in the next two weeks. https://www.al-monitor.com/originals/2022/01/hints-progress-iran-nuclear-talks-time-running-out

US will likely want a revised JCPOA to cap the uranium enrichment level, which is currently exceeding 60% per ecfr.eu article by Julien barnes-Dacey, dated January 13, 2022. Iran will likely not want another agreement. Iran is accustomed to the sanctions and its revenue is supported by exporting Iranian oil indirectly to China. Therefore, 50-50 split but with so many issues going on (Russia's threat on Ukraine, midterm elections), JCPOA will not be a priority.

If the Biden administration wanted this deal they could have had it their first day. All they had to do was lower sanctions and at that time I'm confident Iran would have rejoined the original agreement. However the Biden administration took the same position as the Trump administration that the original deal was not acceptable and used the sanctions as leverage to try to get additional concessions such as restrictions on missiles. Which is disingenuous because the Biden negotiating team has many of the same people that negotiated the original deal under Obama.
Basically, at this stage the problem is that there is no way - apparently - to guarantee that the US won't get out of the agreement just it did in 2018.

Skeptical on the assumption that on average these types of negotiations take maybe a little over 2 years until an outcome is reached. Perhaps it should be lower in style of Fermi-izing. But I won't do that because historically, this has yielded me mediocre results.

Negotiations to revive the JCPOA have reportedly been progressing, albeit without much US involvement. That said, I assume the US is nonetheless involved in the background - it's hard to see why they wouldn't be - and they have indicated a will to get back in. Politically, this might also Biden the chance to market something as a win to his supporters (Republicans will bash him either way), which may be necessary depending on how other events progress (Ukraine, China relations, midterms).
There is some pretty blunt talk in recent news about the risks of talks failing, which means they are probably closer to failing than succeeding.
At this point, there may be no version of the JCPOA on offer for much longer. Besides, chatting with Iran is likely to be politically harmful here in The Home Of The Brave. Stay tuned.
